Title : Aimee Parkison
Text : '''Aimee Parkison''' is an award-winning short story writer and novelist.  She has taught creative writing at a number of universities, including [[Cornell University]], the [[University of North Carolina at Charlotte]], and [[Oklahoma State University]].

==Biography==

Parkison earned her Bachelor of Arts in English Language and Literature/Letters from [[Oklahoma State University]] in 2000, where she was Art Editor and Fiction Editor of ''Papyrus'', the undergraduate literary magazine. She earned her Master of Fine Arts from [[Cornell University]] in 2002, and taught there as a lecturer of Creative Writing from September 2002 to May 2004.

Parkison worked as an Associate Professor of English at the [[University of North Carolina at Charlotte]],<ref name="UNCC">{{cite web|url=http://clas-pages.uncc.edu/aimee-parkison |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-04-26 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140427044129/http://clas-pages.uncc.edu/aimee-parkison/ |archivedate=2014-04-27 }}</ref> where she taught Creative Writing, including fiction, poetry, and screenwriting. Parkison was the Creative Writing Coordinator of the English Department the faculty sponsor and chapter adviser for the UNC-C [[Sigma Tau Delta]], Beta Sigma Chapter.

Parkison became an Assistant Professor of Creative Writing-Fiction at Oklahoma State University in May 2014.

==Fiction==
Winner of the FC2 Catherine Doctorow Innovative Fiction Prize<ref name="fc2.org">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fc2.org/authors/parkinson/|title=Aimee Parkison}}</ref><ref name="uapress.ua.edu">{{Cite web|url=http://www.uapress.ua.edu/product/978-1-57366-871-2-Refrigerated-Music-for-a-Gleaming-Woman,6567.aspx?skuid=3465|title=Refrigerated Music for a Gleaming Woman - University of Alabama Press|website=www.uapress.ua.edu}}</ref> as well as the first annual Starcherone Fiction Prize, Parkison is the author of three short story collections and one novel.  Parkison’s prose and poetry have appeared in literary magazines, anthologies, and academic journals. Her short story collection, ''Woman With the Dark Horses'' (2004), was selected by [[Cris Mazza]] for the first annual Starcherone Prize.<ref name="Starcherone Prize">{{cite web|url=http://www.starcherone.com/prize.htm |title=Previous Winners |publisher=Starcherone Books |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151212231304/http://www.starcherone.com/prize.htm |archivedate=2015-12-12 }}</ref> Parkison's second short story collection, ''The Innocent Party'', was published by [[BOA Editions]]<ref name="BOA Editions">{{cite web|url=http://www.boaeditions.org/authors/Aimee-Parkison |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-04-26 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140427014912/http://www.boaeditions.org/authors/Aimee-Parkison |archivedate=2014-04-27 }}</ref> in 2012.

Her fourth book, a story collection entitled ''Refrigerated Music for a Gleaming Woman,'' was published by FC2 in 2017 and won the Catherine Doctorow Innovative Fiction Prize.<ref name="fc2.org"/><ref name="uapress.ua.edu"/>

She was awarded a North Carolina Arts Council Fellowship<ref>{{cite web|title=Individual Artist: Aimee Parkison: Literature Fiction|url=http://search.ncarts.org/fellowship_details.php?id=281&type=art|publisher=North Carolina Arts Council}}</ref>  in Prose Writing and a Hearst Fellowship from the [[American Antiquarian Society]]<ref name="American Antiquarian Society">{{cite web|url=https://www.americanantiquarian.org/pastartistfellows.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-04-26 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326165435/http://www.americanantiquarian.org/pastartistfellows.htm |archivedate=2015-03-26 }}</ref> Her most recent short poetic novel called [https://www.amazon.com/Petals-Your-Eyes-Aimee-Parkison/dp/1938603206/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1399829053&sr=8-1&keywords=petals+of+your+eyes%27 The Petals of Your Eyes], about kidnapped girls who become actors in a secret theater was published in May 2014.

Parkison regularly holds fiction readings and writing workshops at colleges throughout the country. She will also participate in the Association of Writers & Writing Programs Conference [[Association of Writers & Writing Programs]] 2014 in Seattle. As part of the Women Writing Violence panel, she will discuss how today’s literature often ignores the trend of "Women Writing Violence." She is now working on a new story collection, a screenplay, and a historical novel.

She has received a [[Christopher Isherwood]] Fellowship,<ref name="Association of Writers & Writing Programs">{{Cite web|url=http://awpwriter.org/|title=AWP: Directory of Members|website=awpwriter.org}}</ref> a Writers at Work Fellowship, and a Kurt Vonnegut Fiction Prize <ref>{{cite web|title=Kurt Vonnegut Prize Winners|url=http://webdelsol.com/NorthAmReview/NAR/NAR/Kurt%20Vonnegut%20Fiction%20Prize%20Winners.html|work=2004 Winner; Warnings|publisher=North American Review}}</ref>  from the [[North American Review]], the oldest literary magazine in the US.<ref>{{cite web|title=North American Review|url=http://www.northamericanreview.org/|publisher=North American Review}}</ref>

Her primary areas of interest include fiction writing, creative nonfiction, screenwriting and film studies and women’s studies. She currently is working on a new story collection, a screenplay, and a historical novel.

==Reviews==
In addition to fiction writing, Parkison has written a review titled "All the Pretty Things;" an evaluation of ''The Beautiful Anthology'' that appeared in the American Book Review.  Vol. 33, No. 5: 20.

==Books==
* ''The Petals of Your Eyes''.  Starcherone Books, Buffalo, NY: May 13, 2014. {{ISBN|978-1938603204}}
* ''The Innocent Party''.  BOA Editions, Ltd. (American Reader Series), Rochester, NY: April 17, 2012.  {{ISBN|978-1934414866}}
* ''Woman with Dark Horses''.  Starcherone Press: Buffalo, NY:  January 1, 2004. [Note:  This book, a short story collection, was the winner of the 2003 Starcherone Fiction Prize.] {{ISBN|978-0970316554}}
* ''Refrigerated Music for a Gleaming Woman.<ref name="fc2.org"/><ref name="fc2.org"/>'' FC2/University of Alabama Press, Tuscaloosa: March 7, 2017. {{ISBN|978-1573660600}}<ref>https://www.amazon.com/Refrigerated-Music-Gleaming-Woman-Stories/dp/1573660604/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1489964141&sr=8-1&keywords=aimee+parkison</ref>

==Awards and Distinctions==
*FC2 Catherine Doctorow Innovative Fiction Prize for the story collection, ''Refrigerated Music for a Gleaming Woman,'' selected by contest judge, Stephen Graham Jones <ref name="fc2.org"/><ref name="uapress.ua.edu"/>
*First place in [[North American Review]]’s first annual [[Kurt Vonnegut]] Fiction Prize <ref>{{cite web|title=Kurt Vonnegut Fiction Prize Winners|url=http://webdelsol.com/NorthAmReview/NAR/NAR/Kurt%20Vonnegut%20Fiction%20Prize%20Winners.html|work=2004 Winner: Warnings by Aimee Parkison|publisher=North American Review}}</ref>  for an original short story, “Warnings” in 2004 <ref>{{cite journal|last=Parkison|first=Aimee|title=Warnings|journal=North American Review|date=May–August 2004|volume=May–August 2004|pages=3–8}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Parkison|first=Aimee|title=Warnings|journal=North American Review|volume=May–August 2004|pages=3–8}}</ref><ref name="North Carolina Arts Council">{{cite web|title=Aimee Parkison Literature Fiction Writing|url=http://search.ncarts.org/fellowship_details.php?id=281&type=art|publisher=North Carolina Arts Council}}</ref>
*First Place in Starcherone Press 2003 Fiction Prize for Innovative Writing for the story collection ''Woman with Dark Horses''<ref name="North Carolina Arts Council"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Starcherone Books |url=http://www.starcherone.com/prize.htm |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151212231304/http://www.starcherone.com/prize.htm |archivedate=2015-12-12 }}</ref><ref name="Web Del Sol Chapbook Series">{{cite web|url=http://webdelsol.com/LITARTS/Aimee_Parkison/wds.htm|title=Aimee Parkison|work=Web Del Sol Chapbook Series|publisher=Web Del Sol}}</ref>
*Jack Dyer Fiction Prize for the short story “The Upstairs Album” selected by Carolyn Alessio, prose editor of [[Crab Orchard Review]], 2001<ref>{{cite web|title=Crab Orchard Review's Annual Literary Contests|url=http://craborchardreview.siu.edu/dyer1.html|work="The Upstairs Album' 2001 Winner citation|publisher=Southern Illinois University Carbondale|access-date=2014-05-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512231106/http://craborchardreview.siu.edu/dyer1.html|archive-date=2014-05-12|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref>
*2013 [[William Randolph Hearst]] Creative Artist Fellow, [[American Antiquarian Society]] Fellowship for Creative and Performing Artists and Writers <ref>{{cite web|title=Present and Former Creative and Performing Artist and Writer Fellows |url=https://www.americanantiquarian.org/pastartistfellows.htm |work=2013 Fellowship Winner |publisher=American Antiquarian Society, AAS |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326165435/http://www.americanantiquarian.org/pastartistfellows.htm |archivedate=2015-03-26 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Aimee Parkison: Literature Fiction Writing|url=http://search.ncarts.org/fellowship_details.php?id=281&type=art|publisher=North Carolina Arts Council}}</ref>
